**Claude Projects.** [Navigate to Projects]

If you haven't set up a Project yet, you're leaving the most powerful feature on the table. A Project lets you give Claude a persistent set of instructions — meaning every conversation inside that Project starts with Claude already knowing who you are and how you work.

This is the equivalent of having an employee who never forgets your onboarding conversation.

Here's what a Project system prompt looks like for a real business." [Show or read through an example system prompt — use a coach/consultant scenario]

**Example System Prompt to walk through:**

> You are a business assistant for [Name], a [what they do] who serves [audience]. Your job is to help create content, write emails, and support business operations.
>
> Voice: [3-4 specific voice descriptors — direct, warm, no corporate jargon, etc.]
>
> Never use: [list of words/phrases to avoid]
>
> Always lead with: [format/style preference]
>
> Business context: [offer, pricing, key differentiators]
>
> Current priorities: [active campaign, upcoming launch, etc.]

"See what's happening there? Claude isn't guessing anymore. Every single output starts from a baseline that already knows your business.

Now — for those of you who don't have Claude Pro, or want to use this across tools — there's a second approach. A context file.

A context file is just a document — could be a Google Doc, a Notion page, anything — where you keep your business brief, your voice guide, and your key info. Every time you open a new Claude conversation, you paste it in at the top.

That sounds like extra work. It takes about 15 seconds. And it is the difference between getting generic output and getting something you can actually publish.

Here's what a context file looks like." [Show a simplified example]

**The two takeaways for this segment:**
- Set up a Project with a system prompt if you have Claude Pro
- If not, build a context file and paste it at the top of every session

"The goal is simple: Claude should never start from zero when you're talking to it. Every conversation should start with Claude already knowing your business. Once you do this, everything changes."

